PRESIDENT Cyril Ramaphosa will no longer be appearing before the Zondo Commission on Monday, 31 May. His office issued a statement on Thursday afternoon, 27 May, that it had agreed to a request from the Zondo Commission to postpone Ramaphosa’s hearing. “The presidency can confirm it has agreed to a request from the Commission of Inquiry into State Capture for President Ramaphosa’s scheduled appearance on 31 May and 1 June 2021 to be postponed to a later date,” it said. The presidency said it was in communication with the commission to secure suitable alternative dates for his appearance. This is the second time Ramaphosa’s evidence is being postponed. On Tuesday 25 May, chairman of the commission Deputy Chief Justice Raymond Zondo made the announcement that Ramaphosa was set to appear on 31 May and 1 June in his capacity as president of Mzansi. The initial dates were 28 and 29 April. Commission spokesman Mbuyiselo Stemela said: “I have just been informed that the president of the republic of South Africa, His Excellency, Mr Cyril Ramaphosa will no longer appear at the commission on the 31st May and 1st June 2021 as previously announced.”